
Tic-Tac-Toe Game

Overview
This is a simple console-based Tic-Tac-Toe game implemented in Python. The game can be played between two human players or a human player against the computer. The game board is 3x3, and the objective is to align three of your symbols in a row, column, or diagonal.

Features

Two Player Mode: Play against another person on the same computer.
Single Player Mode: Play against the computer, which makes random moves or attempts to block the player from winning.
Dynamic Board Display: The board adjusts to show moves and game state clearly.
Requirements
Python 3.x
No external libraries are required
How to Run
Clone or Download the repository.

Open a terminal or command prompt.

Navigate to the directory containing the tic_tac_toe.py file.

Run the script using Python:

bash
Copy code
python tic_tac_toe.py
How to Play
Starting the Game:

Upon running the script, you will be prompted to enter the number of players: 1 for playing against the computer, or 2 for playing against another player.
Making a Move:

The game will display the board, and you will be prompted to enter your move. Enter a number between 1 and 9 corresponding to the position on the board.
Winning the Game:

The game will automatically check for a winner after every move. If a player aligns three of their symbols in a row, column, or diagonal, they win.
Ending the Game:

The game will declare a draw if all spots on the board are filled and no player has won.
Code Explanation
Board Representation
The board is a list of 9 elements, initialized with empty spaces.
Each element represents a cell in the 3x3 grid.
    


